        First Order Logic:
            used to represent objects relationships and rule in a structures way,extends propositional logic

            Components:
                1)Constants
                    represent specific objects or entities
                
                2)Variables
                    represent unspecified objects
                
                3)Predicates
                    define properties or relationships
                
                4)Functions
                    map objects to other objects
                
                5)Quantifiers
                    define the scope of other variables
            
            Representation:
                the representation of knowledge through facts object and relationships using logical expressions
            
            inference:
                logical patterns used to derive valid conclusions from given premises

                Laws:
                    1)Law of detachment
                        if a statement is true its conditions is satisfied so the conclusion is true
                    
                    2)Law of Contrapositive
                        if a conditional statement is true and its consequent is false then its antecedent must also be false

                    3)Hypothetical Syllogism
                        if two confitional statements are true where the consequent of the first is the antecedent of the second then a combination of the first antecedent and second consequence is also true
                
                    4)Disjunctive syllogism
                        if a ot statement is true and one input is false the other must be true
                    
                    5)Conjunction 
                        if two statements are true then their conjunction is also true
                    
                    6)Simplification
                        if an and statement is true then each of its conjuncts is also true
                    
                    7)Addition
                        if a statement is true then the disjunction of that statement with another is also true
                    
                    8)Absorption
                        if a conditional statement is true then the antecedent implies a conjunction of itself and the consequent

                    9)Resolution
                        if two disjunctions are true and one contains a proposition while the other contains its negation then the disjuntion of the remaining parts is true 
