Types of Learning:
    Supervised:
        a model learns from labelled data meaning each input has a correct output
        it compares predictions with results and improves over time to increase accuracy of predictions

        Types:
            1)Linear Regression
                predicts continuos values assuminh there is a linear relationship between input and output
                uses a line of best fit to predict 
                input = independant variable
                output = dependant variable

                there is a hypothesis function that makes predictions

                Gradient descent is used to train a model by minimizing the prediction error

                Types:
                    1)Simple
                        only one dependant and independant

                        prediction formula:
                            y = t+tx
                    
                    2)Multiple 
                        multiple independant variable but one dependant

                        prediction formula:
                            y= t +tx1 +tx2 + tx3 ... +txn
                        
                Assumptions:
                    Linearity
                        the relationship between independant and dependant variables are linear
                    
                    Independence of Errors
                        error in prediction should not affect other predictions
                    
                    Constant Variance
                        errors have equal spread across all vakues of the independant variable(spread of values should be constant)
                    
                    Normality
                        errors should follow a normal distribution
                    
                    Multicollinearity
                        input variables shouldnt be closely related(relative)
                    
                    Additivity
                        the effect on Y is the sum of effects from each X

            2)Logistic Regression
                predicts binary output variable

                Types:
                    1)Binomial 
                        used when the dependant variable has binary 
                    
                    2)Multinomial
                        used when the dependant has three or more categories
                    
                    3)Ordinal
                        dependat has three or more categories with a natural order(it considers the order when making predictions)
                    
                Assumptions
                    independent observations
                        each data points is independant of others
                    
                    Binary dependent 
                        the target variable is binary (T or F not applicable to multimodal)
                    
                    Linearity of Log Odds
                        independant variable shave linear relationship with the lof odds of the dependant variable
                    
                    No Extreme outlers

                    Large Sample size

            3)Decision trees
                uses tree where each node is a decition and each leaf is an outcome
            
            4)Random Forrest
                combines decision trees 

                Assumptions:
                    Each tree mmakes its own predictions irrelevant of others

                    trees are built with random samples

                    Enough data ensures trees are different and learn unique patterns and variety

                    Different predictions improve accuracy
            
            5)Support Vector Machine
                seperated data into classes using a boumdary
                finds the best boundary plane between diferent classes of data

                Concepts:
                    HyperPlane
                        decision boundary seperating classes
                    
                    Support Vectors
                        closest data points to the hypper plane
                    
                    Margin
                        distance between hyperplane and support vectors
                    
                    Kernel
                        maps data to a higher dimensional plane
                    
                    Hard Margin
                        a maximum margin that seperates data with no missclassifications
                    
                    Soft Margin
                        aallows for some miscalculations by using slack variables

                    C
                        a regularisation term balancing margin  penalties and rewards, a higher c forces stricter penalty for miscalcs
                    
                    Hinge Loss
                        a loss function penalizing misscalced points
                    
                    Dual Problem
                        solving lagrange multipliers associated with support vectors, allows kernal trick
            
            6)K-Nearest Neighbours
                predicts based off of closest data points
                lazy learner algorithm

                K for nearest neighbour or neighbours

                uses:
                    validation for selecting K:
                        Cross validation

                        Elbow method

                        Odd values
                
                calculates a distance between prediction and K
            
            7)Gradiemt Boosting
                corrects errors of previous models to improve
            
            8)Naive Bayes
                uses Baues theorem assuming features are independant
                predicts the category of a data point using probability 

                ie: if all of one group in one area then more data from group should be in that area

                Assumptions:
                    Feature Independence

                    Continuos features are normally distributed

                    Discrete features have multinomial distributions

                    Features are important

                    All Data is present

    Semi-Supervised:
        uses small amounts of labeled data and large amounts of unlabeled data to improve model performance

        Working:
            Self Training
                ,odel is trained on labeled data then predicts labels for unlabeled data adding high confidence predictions to the labeled set

            Co Training
                two models trained on different feature subsets of data model labels unlabeled data for the other (peer learning)
            
            MultiView
                a variation of cotraining where models train on different daata representations to predict the same outputs    
            Graph based
                data represented as nodes on graph and esges as imilarities of data points
                labels propatgated from labeled nodes to unlabeled ones based on graph connectivity
            
        Limitations:
            requires good architecture and hyper prarameters

            Unlabeled data may contain errors

            relies on assumptions such as data consistency which may not be true to every case

            assessing performance is difficult due to limited labeled data
    
    Unsupervised:
        model works without labelled data learning patterns without human input(labels or preidentified patterns)

        Types:
            1)Clustering
                groups unlabeled data into clusters of similarity in order to find patterns relationships without prior knowledge

                K means clustering
                    group into clusters by applying KNN where k represents the number of groups we can classify into

                    steps:
                        Initialisation
                            (selecting cluster centroids)
                        
                        Assignment Step
                            data points assigned to centroids to cluster
                        
                        Update
                            recalculate the centroids
                        
                        Repeat
                            repeat until centroids dont change
                
                Density based clustering:
                    DBSCAN groups data points closely packed togehter and marks outliers as noise

                    Paramaters:
                        1)eps
                            radius of neighbourhood around a point(if less than or equal to eps then points considered neighbourly)
                            analyze k-distance 
                        
                        2)MinPts
                            minimum points required within eps radius to form a dense region

            2)Association Rule Learning
                rule based learning in form of if then rules

                Hierarchical
                    groups into a tree structure
                    
                    Dendrogram
                        family tree of clusters
                        shows how points or subgroups merge together into different groups
                    
                    Types:
                        Agglomerative
                            bottom up approach(point to sub to group)
                        
                        Divisive
                            top down(Group to sub to point)
                        
                    Methods:
                        for grouping clusters diff  methods:
                            Min
                                the minimum distance between any two points of the cluster
                            
                            Max
                                the maximum distance between any two points of the cluster
                            
                            Group Average
                                average distance between points
                            
                            Wards
                                similarity of two clusters based on increase in squared error when merged

            3)Dimensionality Reduction
                decreasing the number of features or variables in a dataset while retaining as much og info as possible

                Principality component analysis:
                    PCA reduces features in a dataset by correlating the most important information or overarching into a different dataset

                    (very cool uses eigenvectors and values)
    
    Reinforcement Learning: 
        learning through trial and errir to maximize cumulative rewards
        requires a feedback loop through rewards and penalties for learning by using a weighted mean to calculate optimum outputs.

        Components:
            1)Policy
                agents behaviour(states for actions)
            
            2)Reward Signal
                guides agents by providing feedback 
            
            3)Value function 
                evaluate long term goals to immediate rewards(higher desireability to do well in later stages etc)

            4)Model
                simulation of the environment and its predit=ctions
        
        Q-Learning:
            popular model,learns through interactions with environment learning purely from experience 

            Components:
                1)Q values
                    the expected rewards for moving to a specific state through action
                
                2)Rewards
                    move through state recieving rewards until reaching a terminal state
                    (FSM)
                
                3)Temporal Difference
                    agent updates using a formula involving the 
                    
                    current state
                    
                    next state 
                    
                    action taken next best 
                    
                    action reward recieved for action
                    
                    gamma - discount acting to balance immediate and future rewards

                    alpha - learning rate(how fast old Q values are changing)
                
                4)epsilon greedy policy(exploration vs exploitation)
                    decides which  action to take based on current Q estimates

                    Exploitation
                        highest Q with 1- epsilon
                    
                    Exploration
                        probability epsilon
            
            Determination of Q:
                1)Temporal difference
                    comparing values between states and actions with previous actions and states to learn
                
                2)Bellmans equations#   recursive formula used to calculate value of a given state

        Deep Q Learning:
            uses deep learning when states is very large ie(large scope to effect of actions resulting in many possibilities)

            Architecture:
                Network - aproximates q value 
                
                Experience replay - store past experiences in replay buffer sample from this during training

                Target Network - a seperate target network holding the paramaters theta minus used to compute the target Q values
    
    Deep Learning:
        the learning through mimicry of the human brain through neural networks to autonomously gain intelligence

        Deep learning is a type of machine learning

        Neural Networks:
            layers of nodes collaborating to process raw input data
            flows through multiple layers of neurons where each neuron applies a transformation

            Components:
                1)Input layer
                    recieving information
                
                2)Hidden Layers
                    process data recieved
                
                3)output
                    decision prediction made to input

            Backpropogation
                if a result ended in a positive or negative, the actions taken to reach the state gain a negative or positive weight depending on the outcome

            Neurons:
                different neurons relate to different layers
                works similar to a real neuron with inputs a function an activation function and an output
                

            Types:
                1)feedforward
                    data flows linearly from input to output
                        , no loops or feedback involved
                    
                    activation functions enable the learning of more complext data patterns:
                        Sigmoid , Tanh , ReLU
                
                2)Convolutional
                    use layers to detect spatial hierarchies 

                    Components not in others:
                        CNN runs on covents which is a sequence of layer transforms of differentiable functions

                        Convolutional Layer:
                            extracts important features applying filters(kernels) to compute dot product between filter weights and image patches to create maps
                        
                        Pooling
                            reduces the spatial dimensions of feature maps 
                        
                        Flattening
                            converts multidimensional feature maps into one dimensional vector
                
                3)Recurrent
                    process sequential data ,use loops o retain information over time

                    Components:
                        Recurrent Neurons
                            hold a state that remembers previous inputs in sequence(stack/queue)allowing dependancy across time
                        
                        Unfolding
                            expanding the recurrent structure 

                4)generative Adversial
                    a generator and discriminator network that compete to create data
                
                5)AutoEncoders
                    unsupervised that learn efficient data encodings through compression of input into latent and reconstruction
                
                6)transformer
                    natural language processing with self attention mechanisms

                7)Radial Basis Function
                    work with data that can be modelled on a cirular or maps to a radial basis function
                
                8)Long Short Term
                    improved RNN capturing long term dependencies in sequential data
                
                    uses a forget gate to determine which information should be removed from memory

                9)Gated Recurrent Unit
                    reduces complexity when solving sequential data,simplified LSTMs

                    discard irrelevant information

            Perceptron
                a single layer perceptron in a single neuton
                    recieve input , process and decide to activate or not then send oujtput to next neuron or system
                
                Multilayer made of layers of dingle neutrons 
                uses forward  propogation and a lossfunction and back propogation
            
            Artificial Neural Networks
                1)initialize weights and bias

                2)Feed input data

                3)Forward propogation

                4)Calculate Error

                5)Backpropagation

                6)Repeat

                7)Test the networks
    
    Probabalistic Models
        consider the uncertainty of real world data to make predictions based on distributions rather than absolute values.

        aim to learn patterns from data and make predictions on new unseen data,allow uncertainty to be modeled into a new set of adata

        Categories:
            1)Generative
                model joint distribution of input and output to generate new data based on the original dataset

            2)Discriminative
                models conditional distribution of the output variable given the input.learn a decision boundary that seperates different classes of the output variable

            3)Graphical
                graphical models that show the conditional dependence
        
        Naive Bayes
            as before ,used for classifying problems
        
        Monte Carlo Simulation
            a method to predict and understand the behavioural systems involving uncertainty
            simulates random inputs to estimate outcomes and their probabilities

            How:
                1)define the problem
                    identify the system or process to simulate
                
                2)Model inputs
                    choose probability distributions to represent the problem
                
                3)Run Simulations
                    generate inputs and record outputs to determine probabilities of outcomes
                
                4)Analyze results
                    look at distribution of results to determin expected outcomes
            
        Expectation Maximization algorithm:
            an iterative optimization technique used to estimate unknown paramaters in probabalistic models

            E-step
                using the current parameter estimates ,calculate expected values of missing or hidden variables
            
            M-step
                updated expectations from the estep then re estimates the model parameters

            Key Concepts:
                1)latent variables
                    variables that arent directly observed but are inferred from the data

                2)Likelihood
                    probability of the observed data given a set of model parameteers

                3)Maximum Likelihood Estimation
                        an approach to estimating parameters by choosing values that maximze the likelihood of observing the data

                4)Log Likelihood
                    the natural logarithms of the likelihood functions

                5)Posterior probability
                    in bayesian inference, this represents the probabilty of parameters given the data and prior knowledge

                6)Convergence
                    stopping criterion for the process,EM converge when updates to parameters 
    
    Generative AI
        Large Language Models
            advanced AI systems built to process understand and generate human text

            Workings:
                Input Embeddings
                    converting text into numerical vectors
                
                Positional Encoding
                    Adding sequence information
                
                Self Attention
                    understanding between words and context
                
                Feed Forward Layers
                    Captures complex patterns
                
                Decoding
                    generates responses
                
                Multi Head Attention
                    Parallel reasoning over multiple relationships
        
        Generative Pre trained transformer
            a ;anguage model that understands human like text. it learns patterns and relationshps of words from large data

            uses pre trainging then fine tuning to get the end result
        
        Bidirectional encoder representations from transformers
            bert alayzes text in both directions  to recognize context

            pre trained  using unlabeled text to learn representations of words based on surrounding context

            Workflow:
                uses a encoder to process input text and generate representations for each token
            
            Masked Language Model
                some words of the input are masked and the model learns to predict these missing worrds using the surrounding context

            Next sentence Prediction
                understand the relationship between two sentences by predicting whether one sentence follows another
            
            Bert uses both MLM and NSP

            bert is then fine tuned on labeled data to adatpt to specific tasks
        
        Text to text transfer transformer
            treats every NLP task as a text to text problem
            formulates encodes decodes and learns in that order to process the information of the inputs

